<DOC><DOCNO> AP890510-0020 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-05-10-89 0203EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i PM-BRF--Austria-Neo-Nazis     05-10 0172</FIRST><SECOND>PM-BRF--Austria-Neo-Nazis,0178</SECOND><HEAD>Three Jailed for Destroying Anti-Nazi Monument</HEAD><DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Three men were sentenced to prison termsof up to three years for firebombing an anti-Fascist memorial inthe southern city of Graz.   The memorial, by German-American sculptor Hans Haacke, was partof an exhibit and arts festival devoted to the country's pasthalf-century.   Austria had been incorporated into Adolf Hitler's Third Reichand Graz was a Nazi stronghold in 1938.   The monument, a wooden obelisk commemorating Jews, gypsies andothers killed by the Nazis, was firebombed on Nov. 2 and severelydamaged.   On Tuesday, a Graz court sentenced Peter Lukas, 37, to threeyears in jail for carrying out the attack. Hubert Steinbrugger, 68,was sentenced to 18 months and Arne Mayer, 24, to one year, both asaccomplices.   The men also were found guilty of Nazi-like activity and fined$77,000, the cost of the damage to the monument.   Steinbrugger was sentenced in 1954 to a 15-month jail term forneo-Nazi activity, according to the Austria Press Agency.</TEXT></DOC>